## 4. `requestInfo` — AsyncLocalStorage-based Request Context

```typescript
interface RequestInfo<Params = any, AppContext = DefaultAppContext> {
  request: Request;
  path: string;
  params: Params;
  ctx: AppContext;      // User-defined context object
  rw: RwContext;
  cf: ExecutionContext;
  response: ResponseInit & { headers: Headers };
  isAction: boolean;
}

interface DefaultAppContext {} // Empty by default, extend via declaration merging

type RwContext = {
  nonce: string;
  Document: React.FC<DocumentProps<any>>;
  rscPayload: boolean;
  ssr: boolean;
  databases: Map<string, Kysely<any>>;
  scriptsToBeLoaded: Set<string>;
  entryScripts: Set<string>;
  inlineScripts: Set<string>;
  pageRouteResolved: PromiseWithResolvers<void> | undefined;
  actionResult?: unknown;
  renderError?: unknown;
};
```

Access via the reactive proxy (works in server actions, middleware, route handlers):

```typescript
import { requestInfo } from "rwsdk/worker";

// Access current request info anywhere in the request lifecycle
const { request, ctx, params } = requestInfo;
```

Or explicitly:

```typescript
import { getRequestInfo } from "rwsdk/worker";
const info = getRequestInfo(); // throws if called outside request context
```

You can set response headers/status via `requestInfo.response`:

```typescript
requestInfo.response.headers.set("X-Custom", "value");
requestInfo.response.status = 201;
```

The `ctx` object is a mutable `Record<string, any>` that persists across middleware and handlers in the same request. This is where interruptors store data (e.g., `ctx.user = session.user`).

